{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":1317,"text":"How do you find a dinosaur?"},{"time":3928,"text":"Sounds impossible, doesn't it?"},{"time":6650,"text":"It's not."},{"time":7969,"text":"And the answer relies on a formula\nthat all paleontologists use."},{"time":12722,"text":"And I'm going to tell you the secret."}]},{"cues":[{"time":15350,"text":"First, find rocks of the right age."},{"time":19226,"text":"Second, those rocks\nmust be sedimentary rocks."},{"time":23863,"text":"And third, layers of those rocks\nmust be naturally exposed."},{"time":28768,"text":"That's it."},{"time":29943,"text":"Find those three things\nand get yourself on the ground,"},{"time":33378,"text":"chances are good\nthat you will find fossils."}]},{"cues":[{"time":36313,"text":"Now let me break down this formula."},{"time":38812,"text":"Organisms exist only during certain\ngeological intervals."},{"time":43207,"text":"So you have to find\nrocks of the right age,"},{"time":45661,"text":"depending on what your interests are."},{"time":47853,"text":"If you want to find trilobites,"},{"time":49387,"text":"you have to find the really,\nreally old rocks of the Paleozoic --"},{"time":52562,"text":"rocks between a half a billion\nand a quarter-billion years old."},{"time":56306,"text":"Now, if you want to find dinosaurs,"},{"time":58418,"text":"don't look in the Paleozoic,\nyou won't find them."},{"time":60799,"text":"They hadn't evolved yet."},{"time":62304,"text":"You have to find the younger\nrocks of the Mesozoic,"},{"time":65415,"text":"and in the case of dinosaurs,"},{"time":66836,"text":"between 235 and 66 million years ago."}]},{"cues":[{"time":71495,"text":"Now, it's fairly easy to find rocks\nof the right age at this point,"},{"time":74694,"text":"because the Earth is, to a coarse degree,"},{"time":77850,"text":"geologically mapped."},{"time":79578,"text":"This is hard-won information."},{"time":82323,"text":"The annals of Earth history\nare written in rocks,"},{"time":85151,"text":"one chapter upon the next,"},{"time":86476,"text":"such that the oldest pages are on bottom"},{"time":89104,"text":"and the youngest on top."}]},{"cues":[{"time":91583,"text":"Now, were it quite that easy,\ngeologists would rejoice."},{"time":95660,"text":"It's not."},{"time":96942,"text":"The library of Earth is an old one."},{"time":99020,"text":"It has no librarian to impose order."},{"time":102111,"text":"Operating over vast swaths of time,"},{"time":105265,"text":"myriad geological processes\noffer every possible insult"},{"time":110136,"text":"to the rocks of ages."},{"time":112277,"text":"Most pages are destroyed\nsoon after being written."},{"time":115410,"text":"Some pages are overwritten,"},{"time":117186,"text":"creating difficult-to-decipher palimpsests\nof long-gone landscapes."},{"time":122384,"text":"Pages that do find sanctuary\nunder the advancing sands of time"},{"time":127173,"text":"are never truly safe."},{"time":129410,"text":"Unlike the Moon --\nour dead, rocky companion --"},{"time":132778,"text":"the Earth is alive, pulsing\nwith creative and destructive forces"},{"time":136442,"text":"that power its geological metabolism."},{"time":139864,"text":"Lunar rocks brought back\nby the Apollo astronauts"},{"time":142261,"text":"all date back to about the age\nof the Solar System."},{"time":145609,"text":"Moon rocks are forever."},{"time":148960,"text":"Earth rocks, on the other hand,\nface the perils of a living lithosphere."},{"time":153110,"text":"All will suffer ruination,"},{"time":154718,"text":"through some combination\nof mutilation, compression,"},{"time":157568,"text":"folding, tearing, scorching and baking."}]},{"cues":[{"time":161140,"text":"Thus, the volumes of Earth history\nare incomplete and disheveled."},{"time":167079,"text":"The library is vast and magnificent --"},{"time":171964,"text":"but decrepit."},{"time":174273,"text":"And it was this tattered complexity\nin the rock record"},{"time":177163,"text":"that obscured its meaning\nuntil relatively recently."},{"time":181031,"text":"Nature provided no card catalog\nfor geologists --"},{"time":183381,"text":"this would have to be invented."},{"time":186079,"text":"Five thousand years after the Sumerians\nlearned to record their thoughts"},{"time":189734,"text":"on clay tablets,"},{"time":190910,"text":"the Earth's volumes remained\ninscrutable to humans."},{"time":194495,"text":"We were geologically illiterate,"},{"time":197637,"text":"unaware of the antiquity\nof our own planet"},{"time":200843,"text":"and ignorant of our connection"},{"time":202376,"text":"to deep time."}]},{"cues":[{"time":205040,"text":"It wasn't until the turn\nof the 19th century"},{"time":208240,"text":"that our blinders were removed,"},{"time":210660,"text":"first, with the publication\nof James Hutton's \"Theory of the Earth,\""},{"time":215078,"text":"in which he told us that the Earth\nreveals no vestige of a beginning"},{"time":218974,"text":"and no prospect of an end;"},{"time":221545,"text":"and then, with the printing\nof William Smith's map of Britain,"},{"time":225515,"text":"the first country-scale geological map,"},{"time":227724,"text":"giving us for the first time"},{"time":229114,"text":"predictive insight into where\ncertain types of rocks might occur."},{"time":233504,"text":"After that, you could say things like,"},{"time":235551,"text":"\"If we go over there,\nwe should be in the Jurassic,\""},{"time":238578,"text":"or, \"If we go up over that hill,\nwe should find the Cretaceous.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":243129,"text":"So now, if you want to find trilobites,"},{"time":246008,"text":"get yourself a good geological map"},{"time":248161,"text":"and go to the rocks of the Paleozoic."},{"time":251023,"text":"If you want to find dinosaurs like I do,"},{"time":253366,"text":"find the rocks of Mesozoic and go there."},{"time":257217,"text":"Now of course, you can only make\na fossil in a sedimentary rock,"},{"time":260340,"text":"a rock made by sand and mud."},{"time":262489,"text":"You can't have a fossil"},{"time":263680,"text":"in an igneous rock formed\nby magma, like a granite,"},{"time":267028,"text":"or in a metamorphic rock\nthat's been heated and squeezed."},{"time":270773,"text":"And you have to get yourself in a desert."},{"time":273378,"text":"It's not that dinosaurs\nparticularly lived in deserts;"},{"time":276483,"text":"they lived on every land mass"},{"time":278071,"text":"and in every imaginable environment."},{"time":280596,"text":"It's that you need to go to a place\nthat's a desert today,"},{"time":283565,"text":"a place that doesn't have\ntoo many plants covering up the rocks,"},{"time":286763,"text":"and a place where erosion is always\nexposing new bones at the surface."},{"time":291302,"text":"So find those three things:"},{"time":292859,"text":"rocks of the right age,"},{"time":294438,"text":"that are sedimentary rocks, in a desert,"},{"time":297511,"text":"and get yourself on the ground,"},{"time":299092,"text":"and you literally walk"},{"time":300628,"text":"until you see a bone\nsticking out of the rock."}]},{"cues":[{"time":304562,"text":"Here's a picture that I took\nin Southern Patagonia."},{"time":308347,"text":"Every pebble that you see\non the ground there"},{"time":311133,"text":"is a piece of dinosaur bone."},{"time":313478,"text":"So when you're in that right situation,"},{"time":315368,"text":"it's not a question of whether\nyou'll find fossils or not;"},{"time":318146,"text":"you're going to find fossils."},{"time":319559,"text":"The question is: Will you find something\nthat is scientifically significant?"},{"time":323631,"text":"And to help with that, I'm going to add\na fourth part to our formula,"},{"time":327625,"text":"which is this:"},{"time":329431,"text":"get as far away from other\npaleontologists as possible."}]},{"cues":[{"time":332915,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":334910,"text":"It's not that I don't like\nother paleontologists."},{"time":337289,"text":"When you go to a place\nthat's relatively unexplored,"},{"time":339838,"text":"you have a much better chance\nof not only finding fossils"},{"time":342676,"text":"but of finding something\nthat's new to science."},{"time":345788,"text":"So that's my formula\nfor finding dinosaurs,"},{"time":347923,"text":"and I've applied it all around the world."}]},{"cues":[{"time":349980,"text":"In the austral summer of 2004,"},{"time":352332,"text":"I went to the bottom of South America,"},{"time":354181,"text":"to the bottom of Patagonia, Argentina,"},{"time":356322,"text":"to prospect for dinosaurs:"},{"time":358599,"text":"a place that had terrestrial\nsedimentary rocks of the right age,"},{"time":361996,"text":"in a desert,"},{"time":363223,"text":"a place that had been barely visited\nby paleontologists."},{"time":367166,"text":"And we found this."},{"time":369206,"text":"This is a femur, a thigh bone,"},{"time":371343,"text":"of a giant, plant-eating dinosaur."},{"time":373736,"text":"That bone is 2.2 meters across."},{"time":376594,"text":"That's over seven feet long."}]},{"cues":[{"time":379807,"text":"Now, unfortunately,\nthat bone was isolated."},{"time":381931,"text":"We dug and dug and dug,\nand there wasn't another bone around."},{"time":384994,"text":"But it made us hungry to go back\nthe next year for more."},{"time":387713,"text":"And on the first day\nof that next field season,"},{"time":390340,"text":"I found this: another two-meter femur,"},{"time":393733,"text":"only this time not isolated,"},{"time":395400,"text":"this time associated with 145 other bones"},{"time":398519,"text":"of a giant plant eater."},{"time":401064,"text":"And after three more hard,\nreally brutal field seasons,"},{"time":405184,"text":"the quarry came to look like this."},{"time":407597,"text":"And there you see the tail\nof that great beast wrapping around me."},{"time":411739,"text":"The giant that lay in this grave,\nthe new species of dinosaur,"},{"time":415315,"text":"we would eventually call\n\"Dreadnoughtus schrani.\""},{"time":419513,"text":"Dreadnoughtus was 85 feet\nfrom snout to tail."},{"time":423030,"text":"It stood two-and-a-half stories\nat the shoulder,"},{"time":426217,"text":"and all fleshed out in life,\nit weighed 65 tons."},{"time":431290,"text":"People ask me sometimes,\n\"Was Dreadnoughtus bigger than a T. rex?\""},{"time":434896,"text":"That's the mass of eight or nine T. rex."}]},{"cues":[{"time":438669,"text":"Now, one of the really cool things\nabout being a paleontologist"},{"time":441733,"text":"is when you find a new species,\nyou get to name it."},{"time":444526,"text":"And I've always thought it a shame\nthat these giant, plant-eating dinosaurs"},{"time":448384,"text":"are too often portrayed as passive,\nlumbering platters of meat"},{"time":452887,"text":"on the landscape."}]},{"cues":[{"time":454156,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":455585,"text":"They're not."},{"time":456908,"text":"Big herbivores can be surly,\nand they can be territorial --"},{"time":459951,"text":"you do not want to mess with a hippo\nor a rhino or a water buffalo."},{"time":464871,"text":"The bison in Yellowstone injure\nfar more people than do the grizzly bears."},{"time":469846,"text":"So can you imagine a big bull,\n65-ton Dreadnoughtus"},{"time":475011,"text":"in the breeding season,"},{"time":476738,"text":"defending a territory?"},{"time":478990,"text":"That animal would have been\nincredibly dangerous,"},{"time":481334,"text":"a menace to all around, and itself\nwould have had nothing to fear."},{"time":486507,"text":"And thus the name, \"Dreadnoughtus,\""},{"time":488756,"text":"or, \"fears nothing.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":492047,"text":"Now, to grow so large,"},{"time":493237,"text":"an animal like Dreadnoughtus\nwould've had to have been"},{"time":495873,"text":"a model of efficiency."},{"time":497054,"text":"That long neck and long tail help it\nradiate heat into the environment,"},{"time":500841,"text":"passively controlling its temperature."},{"time":503403,"text":"And that long neck also serves\nas a super-efficient feeding mechanism."},{"time":506932,"text":"Dreadnoughtus could stand\nin one place and with that neck"},{"time":509736,"text":"clear out a huge envelope of vegetation,"},{"time":512052,"text":"taking in tens of thousands of calories\nwhile expending very few."},{"time":516621,"text":"And these animals evolved\na bulldog-like wide-gait stance,"},{"time":520945,"text":"giving them immense stability,"},{"time":523625,"text":"because when you're 65 tons,\nwhen you're literally as big as a house,"},{"time":527725,"text":"the penalty for falling over"},{"time":529856,"text":"is death."},{"time":531677,"text":"Yeah, these animals are big and tough,"},{"time":533606,"text":"but they won't take a blow like that."},{"time":535407,"text":"Dreadnoughtus falls over,\nribs break and pierce lungs."},{"time":538012,"text":"Organs burst."},{"time":539561,"text":"If you're a big 65-ton Dreadnoughtus,"},{"time":541371,"text":"you don't get to fall down\nin life -- even once."}]},{"cues":[{"time":545664,"text":"Now, after this particular\nDreadnoughtus carcass was buried"},{"time":549254,"text":"and de-fleshed by a multitude\nof bacteria, worms and insects,"},{"time":553998,"text":"its bones underwent a brief metamorphosis,"},{"time":556187,"text":"exchanging molecules with the groundwater"},{"time":558227,"text":"and becoming more and more\nlike the entombing rock."},{"time":561603,"text":"As layer upon layer\nof sediment accumulated,"},{"time":564003,"text":"pressure from all sides\nweighed in like a stony glove"},{"time":566853,"text":"whose firm and enduring grip held\neach bone in a stabilizing embrace."}]},{"cues":[{"time":573654,"text":"And then came the long ..."},{"time":576044,"text":"nothing."},{"time":577868,"text":"Epoch after epoch of sameness,"},{"time":581210,"text":"nonevents without number."},{"time":583501,"text":"All the while, the skeleton lay\neverlasting and unchanging"},{"time":586947,"text":"in perfect equilibrium"},{"time":589334,"text":"within its rocky grave."},{"time":591995,"text":"Meanwhile, Earth history unfolded above."},{"time":594036,"text":"The dinosaurs would reign\nfor another 12 million years"},{"time":596707,"text":"before their hegemony was snuffed out\nin a fiery apocalypse."},{"time":601542,"text":"The continents drifted. The mammals rose."},{"time":604244,"text":"The Ice Age came."}]},{"cues":[{"time":606623,"text":"And then, in East Africa,"},{"time":608894,"text":"an unpromising species of ape\nevolved the odd trick of sentient thought."},{"time":615752,"text":"These brainy primates were not\nparticularly fast or strong."},{"time":620062,"text":"But they excelled at covering ground,"},{"time":622292,"text":"and in a remarkable diaspora"},{"time":624185,"text":"surpassing even the dinosaurs' record\nof territorial conquest,"},{"time":627351,"text":"they dispersed across the planet,"},{"time":629305,"text":"ravishing every ecosystem\nthey encountered,"},{"time":632509,"text":"along the way, inventing culture\nand metalworking and painting"},{"time":635714,"text":"and dance and music"},{"time":637786,"text":"and science"},{"time":639793,"text":"and rocket ships that would eventually\ntake 12 particularly excellent apes"},{"time":644346,"text":"to the surface of the Moon."}]},{"cues":[{"time":648900,"text":"With seven billion peripatetic\nHomo sapiens on the planet,"},{"time":653253,"text":"it was perhaps inevitable"},{"time":654494,"text":"that one of them would eventually\ntrod on the grave of the magnificent titan"},{"time":658556,"text":"buried beneath the badlands\nof Southern Patagonia."},{"time":662614,"text":"I was that ape."},{"time":665038,"text":"And standing there, alone in the desert,"},{"time":668640,"text":"it was not lost on me"},{"time":669815,"text":"that the chance of any one individual\nentering the fossil record"},{"time":673469,"text":"is vanishingly small."},{"time":676039,"text":"But the Earth is very, very old."},{"time":678111,"text":"And over vast tracts of time,\nthe improbable becomes the probable."},{"time":682395,"text":"That's the magic of the geological record."},{"time":685110,"text":"Thus, multitudinous creatures\nliving and dying on an old planet"},{"time":688316,"text":"leave behind immense numbers of fossils,"},{"time":690267,"text":"each one a small miracle,"},{"time":692691,"text":"but collectively, inevitable."}]},{"cues":[{"time":696572,"text":"Sixty-six million years ago,\nan asteroid hits the Earth"},{"time":699953,"text":"and wipes out the dinosaurs."},{"time":702771,"text":"This easily might not have been."},{"time":705312,"text":"But we only get one history,\nand it's the one that we have."},{"time":708191,"text":"But this particular reality\nwas not inevitable."},{"time":710491,"text":"The tiniest perturbation\nof that asteroid far from Earth"},{"time":713317,"text":"would have caused it to miss\nour planet by a wide margin."},{"time":716754,"text":"The pivotal, calamitous day during which\nthe dinosaurs were wiped out,"},{"time":720131,"text":"setting the stage\nfor the modern world as we know it"},{"time":723366,"text":"didn't have to be."},{"time":724922,"text":"It could've just been another day --"},{"time":727443,"text":"a Thursday, perhaps --"},{"time":729856,"text":"among the 63 billion days\nalready enjoyed by the dinosaurs."},{"time":735313,"text":"But over geological time,"},{"time":736722,"text":"improbable, nearly impossible events"},{"time":739631,"text":"do occur."},{"time":740806,"text":"Along the path from our wormy,\nCambrian ancestors"},{"time":743753,"text":"to primates dressed in suits,"},{"time":746180,"text":"innumerable forks in the road\nled us to this very particular reality."},{"time":751982,"text":"The bones of Dreadnoughtus\nlay underground for 77 million years."},{"time":756899,"text":"Who could have imagined"},{"time":758094,"text":"that a single species of shrew-like mammal"},{"time":761082,"text":"living in the cracks of the dinosaur world"},{"time":763150,"text":"would evolve into sentient beings"},{"time":765226,"text":"capable of characterizing\nand understanding"},{"time":767606,"text":"the very dinosaurs they must have dreaded?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":772775,"text":"I once stood at the head\nof the Missouri River"},{"time":777107,"text":"and bestraddled it."},{"time":779123,"text":"There, it's nothing more\nthan a gurgle of water"},{"time":781349,"text":"that issues forth from beneath a rock\nin a boulder in a pasture,"},{"time":785984,"text":"high in the Bitterroot Mountains."},{"time":788165,"text":"The stream next to it\nruns a few hundred yards"},{"time":791407,"text":"and ends in a small pond."},{"time":793970,"text":"Those two streams -- they look identical."},{"time":797732,"text":"But one is an anonymous trickle of water,"},{"time":800295,"text":"and the other is the Missouri River."},{"time":803667,"text":"Now go down to the mouth\nof the Missouri, near St. Louis,"},{"time":807188,"text":"and it's pretty obvious\nthat that river is a big deal."},{"time":810640,"text":"But go up into the Bitterroots\nand look at the Missouri,"},{"time":813378,"text":"and human prospection does not\nallow us to see it as anything special."},{"time":819030,"text":"Now go back to the Cretaceous Period"},{"time":821008,"text":"and look at our tiny, fuzzball ancestors."},{"time":823477,"text":"You would never guess"},{"time":824938,"text":"that they would amount\nto anything special,"},{"time":827039,"text":"and they probably wouldn't have,"},{"time":828711,"text":"were it not for that pesky asteroid."}]},{"cues":[{"time":831797,"text":"Now, make a thousand more worlds\nand a thousand more solar systems"},{"time":835182,"text":"and let them run."},{"time":837047,"text":"You will never get the same result."},{"time":839225,"text":"No doubt, those worlds would be\nboth amazing and amazingly improbable,"},{"time":842654,"text":"but they would not be our world\nand they would not have our history."},{"time":845986,"text":"There are an infinite number of histories\nthat we could've had."},{"time":848989,"text":"We only get one, and wow,\ndid we ever get a good one."},{"time":851539,"text":"Dinosaurs like Dreadnoughtus were real."},{"time":855058,"text":"Sea monsters like the mosasaur were real."},{"time":859216,"text":"Dragonflies with the wingspan of an eagle\nand pill bugs the length of a car"},{"time":863336,"text":"really existed."}]},{"cues":[{"time":867192,"text":"Why study the ancient past?"},{"time":870652,"text":"Because it gives us perspective"},{"time":873065,"text":"and humility."},{"time":874977,"text":"The dinosaurs died in the world's\nfifth mass extinction,"},{"time":878433,"text":"snuffed out in a cosmic accident\nthrough no fault of their own."},{"time":883114,"text":"They didn't see it coming,\nand they didn't have a choice."},{"time":888009,"text":"We, on the other hand, do have a choice."},{"time":891943,"text":"And the nature of the fossil record\ntells us that our place on this planet"},{"time":895958,"text":"is both precarious\nand potentially fleeting."},{"time":899127,"text":"Right now, our species is propagating\nan environmental disaster"},{"time":902919,"text":"of geological proportions\nthat is so broad and so severe,"},{"time":906526,"text":"it can rightly be called\nthe sixth extinction."},{"time":910429,"text":"Only unlike the dinosaurs,"},{"time":913128,"text":"we can see it coming."},{"time":915438,"text":"And unlike the dinosaurs,"},{"time":917708,"text":"we can do something about it."},{"time":920406,"text":"That choice is ours."}]},{"cues":[{"time":923490,"text":"Thank you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":924665,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}